<section class="block-section story">
  <span class="section-tag">📖 Story</span>
  <h2>Why this block matters</h2>
  <p class="sub">The unit pivots today. From "how water works" to "who decides who gets it."</p>
  <p>Two big concepts land first. <strong>Water scarcity</strong> isn't one thing — it's two. <em>Physical scarcity</em> = not enough water in the system (Aral Sea, Cape Town's "Day Zero", parts of Yemen). <em>Economic scarcity</em> = water exists but the institutional / infrastructural capacity to deliver it doesn't (much of sub-Saharan Africa, slum settlements in megacities). Chennai's 2019 near-Day-Zero was both — depleted aquifers (physical) plus collapsed institutional response (economic). Most real disputes layer the two.</p>
  <p>Then the <strong>four water-rights frameworks</strong>. They allocate the same physical water differently:</p>
  <ul>
    <li><strong>Riparian rights</strong> — whoever owns the bank owns the use. Long history in English / Indian / common-law systems.</li>
    <li><strong>Prior appropriation</strong> — first to use, first to claim. Dominant in the US West. "Use it or lose it" creates perverse incentives.</li>
    <li><strong>Public trust doctrine</strong> — water is common heritage, government holds it in trust for citizens including future generations.</li>
    <li><strong>Common-pool resource theory</strong> — Elinor Ostrom's Nobel work showing communal management often outperforms private or state ownership. Local irrigation associations as the classic example.</li>
  </ul>
  <p>Each framework gives different stakeholders different claims. Today is also <strong>assignment kickoff</strong>: the <a href="/units/unit-5/assessment-water-stakeholders/">Water Stakeholders Map + Position Paper</a> is assigned, the 8 cases released, the two-tier choice explained. From this block forward, every U5 activity feeds your Position Paper.</p>
</section>

